<h2 class="section-heading">Make your Own Gem</h2>

<p><strong> What is Gem? </strong> 
RubyGems is the official packaging system for <a href="https://www.ruby-lang.org/de/">ruby-lang.org</a>  programming language. It provides a packet format, a tool for managing packages, a repository for their distribution.</p>

<p>Since Ruby 1.9 RubyGems is part of the standard library of Ruby. If you want to use a RubyGem in a Ruby program, you must first load the required library:</p>

<p><strong> Use </strong></p>

<p>RubyGems be accessed via the command line acc.</p>

<stromg> Example :&lt;/strong&gt; 

<div style="overflow:auto; height=200; width=100%;">
<pre style="color:black;background:white;"><pre>

require 'json'        # aktuelle Version
gem 'rake', '= 10.1.0' # mit Versionsangabe


</pre></pre></div> 

<strong>Gem Installation : Rake  </strong>

Download and install rake with the following.
<code> gem install rake </code> 



<strong> Example : </strong> 

First, you must write a â€œRakefileâ€ file which contains the build rules. Here's a simple example:

<div style="overflow:auto; height=200; width=100%;">
<pre style="color:black;background:white;"><pre>

task default: %w[test]

task :test do
  ruby "test/unittest.rb"
end

</pre></pre></div> 

This Rakefile has two tasks:

A task named â€œtestâ€, which â€“ upon invocation â€“ will run a unit test file in Ruby.

A task named â€œdefaultâ€. This task does nothing by itself, but it has exactly one dependency, namely the â€œtestâ€ task. Invoking the â€œdefaultâ€ task will cause Rake to invoke the â€œtestâ€ task as well.

Running the â€œrakeâ€ command without any options will cause it to run the â€œdefaultâ€ task in the Rakefile:

<div style="overflow:auto; height=200; width=100%;">
<pre style="color:black;background:white;"><pre>

% ls
Rakefile     test/
% rake
(in /home/some_user/Projects/rake)
ruby test/unittest.rb
....unit test output here...

</pre></pre></div> 


Type â€œrake â€“helpâ€ for all available options.
